USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It's funny how Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, is so academically intent on repeating the strategy of his predecessor, whom he thought was the dumbest, on Afghanistan.
When he finally got his long-awaited Afghan doctrine out, it turned out he had written it over a copy of Bush's Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the word "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he didn't even hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward".
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh troops into civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and consequently disastrous".
But the months that followed showed that Bush's strategy based on the recommendations of the field commanders was the only one possible and so successful that Iraq is not even mentioned in the news today.
It did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting position than could have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a repeat of the miracle.
The increase in the military contingent was again requested by the field commanders, especially the commander in chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even in spite of his subordinate habits, harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked for 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he seemed to have no choice, so at least he cheated the general out of 10,000 troops.
He managed to squeeze the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic aspect of Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete the process in three years.
Many doubt that a half-hearted increase will yield the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honoring agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are being honored.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces are ill-prepared, accustomed to changing hands every day as they see fit.
Political institutions, even when formally established, will remain a shadow village, with patriarchal tribal relations still flourishing behind it.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult given the ambiguity of the situation, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even building an 'actionable state', which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, does not seem very realistic.
The timeline of Obama's strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and now it's on the verge of explosion.
To believe that a soldier sent into the heat of war to "come home soon" will cause a miracle to happen here can only a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality.
Politically, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is irresponsible, because the Taliban will see it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europe's willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is heading for the negative.
European politicians cannot and will not explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is connected to the war in the Hindu Kush.
Another factor that could radically affect the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions on Iran fail to take effect, the United States will face the difficult question of whether to try to resolve the problem by military force.
The answer to that question will come at a time when, according to Obama, America will move to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election, and therefore plenty of time to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
