Czech discovery: a drug that works on 'toxic' HIV
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works against viruses that have already acquired immunity to the drugs.
This fact outweighs in some cases the fact that the compound does not work as strongly on the common variant of the virus as some of the drugs already available.
AIDS is not yet curable.
However, a combination of medicines that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body can significantly prolong the life of patients.
However, their use is associated with a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral replication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, the University of Heidelberg and the University of Prague is paving the way to tackle virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metal carborans act on a protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metallocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that no other drugs are able to do today, and so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists have come up with new improved compounds based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metallocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A Treacherous and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein in the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV splitting, no mature infectious virus particles would be produced.
By stopping HIV protease, the virus is also stopped from spreading in the patient's body, the researchers explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the researchers describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see chart) are linked by a short organic chain that is then systematically altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of anti-HIV proteases has been tested in a test tube and also against resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metal carborans on the normal enzyme variant is not as strong as that of clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make both metal carborans interesting compounds for further research into the design of effective HIV drugs, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
