The managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the great French companies, our struggle to develop economic intelligence has been futile...
For more than a decade, the management's attitude towards employees in large companies has been reminiscent of the approach taken by companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees identifying with "values" defined from above, as it was before when consumers had to be forced to produce products that stemmed from the ideas of factory heads.
By making the customer the center of business, the marketing revolution has steered market capture strategies in the right direction... even as authoritarian efforts to impose products that differ from customer preferences regularly return!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA and Renault are only a visible part of a much wider phenomenon, which mainly affects managers.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) an active approach and foresight" and requires employees to commit themselves to commitments that are completely at odds with the revenues of authoritarian management.
That's why we're calling for a managerial revolution that puts employees at the center of the enterprise as much as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls.
Will internal opinion polls - like the questionnaire submitted to Orange employees - contribute to a revolution in management practices?
I'm afraid not.
Mainly because I've already convinced myself that in the face of a new situation, the structure, after various turns, preferably returns to what it always did!
Furthermore, because authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of one's failures.
And finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they're engineering graduates, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
For the sake of convenience, they adopt an old behaviorist theory, now revived by US "neuroscientists" and widely circulated without much knowledge by scientific institutions and the media.
The fact that it is possible to leverage management involvement has been shown by a recent Ipsos survey on Figaro.fr, which only reinforces managers in their position of mechanical management, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of the ultimate vision of human behavior.
It is about incorporating a fundamental observation into all management policies and practices: For employees, commitments to the company will only be possible if they appear as a clear means to achieve their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, only studies of motivational functional analysis have addressed this concept of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they assess their enterprises on the basis of a pre-defined dossier which allows them to assess, through the image that the enterprise presents, what it offers them to achieve their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilizing factors, managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their 'social performance' and put their HR management 'on track'.
It thus creates a fertile ground for the development of sound and efficient economic intelligence.
