The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The six-foot-two, five-inch-tall animal ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short front limbs with sickle-like claws, and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, it would be nothing extraordinary.
But Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in the Thursday issue of Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to display these body features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent of Pangaea.
Tawa opens a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the relationships, the expansion and the traits of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, unusual for Triassic sediments, says team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only individual fragments".
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
The discovery is not particularly sensational, but it does support some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of primates is often controversial.
For example, experts debate when lizards split into three major evolutionary lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyranosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and birds; the "long-tailed" four-legged sauropods and their relatives; and the herbivorous ornithischia, which included Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
Tawa hallae is the original theropod, according to analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of the Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs, which are also found in the descendants of theropod birds.
The air sacs make bird breathing more efficient than that of mammals.
In the Tawa hallae, the spinal bones were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation was probably made by a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists concluded that it was there that the lizards first appeared.
According to this, the three lines of evolution soon split and spread from South America to all the continents that then formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangaea.
And the fact that the team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods along with the Tawa hallae would also speak for it.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, scientists argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, one of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His hypothesis could put together a distorted picture, because in South America, there are very many primitive dinosaur fossils that remain, while on other continents, they are rarely found.
How dinosaurs proved to have evolved from a relatively rare secondary line of reptiles into the dominant vertebrates of the Earth during the Earth's Middle Ages remains a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying lizards and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species evolved, while relatives died out and the Triassic and Jurassic intersected.
The success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, which the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but not the reptiles.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted so they could outcompete the competition.
The success story didn't last forever, though.
150 million years later, the meteorite impact helped another group of animals that also evolved in the Triassic and have lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
