75% of working mothers have work-related problems with their childbearing.
Employment discrimination has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who are planning to have a child.
This is the result of a study 'Fertility and working careers of Spanish women' carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market because of motherhood.
The study highlights that at the beginning of cohabitation, there are many differences in views on the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with their partner earlier, have their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable jobs, especially in the public sector, put off cohabitation and motherhood and have fewer children.
"Women aged 35-49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years after they start living with their partner.This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable job and have therefore had to postpone their partnership and the birth of their children.
The type of occupation also has a strong influence on motherhood, albeit less on the length of time spent living with a partner", explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at the CSIC.
Another factor that affects the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of their offspring is their level of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, women with primary and tertiary education had their first child at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with a basic education marry and have their first child before they find a stable job, while women with a secondary or tertiary education, on the other hand, prefer to get a stable job before they marry and have their first child", says Delgado.
