The manual brake assist system is already mandatory equipment.
As with the anti-lock system, ABS, ESP, and the manual brake systems will be mandatory on European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the compulsory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while the deadline for the removal of the deficiency for the others is set at February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU are designed to increase pedestrian protection, and they work by helping to prevent many collisions.
The manual brake assist system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which is detected by the system after the driver steps.
But he can't always keep up the pressure.
According to a study by the automotive parts company Bosch, one third of drivers who are involved in an accident did not apply the brake before the collision, and half of them did not use the brake force to its full potential.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this aid requires the braking system to perform its maximum braking performance, reducing the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be avoided each year.
The reduction in this number will be even more marked - one in four accidents involving persons would be prevented, according to calculations - once so-called intelligent handbrake systems are introduced.
In this case, the vehicle will be equipped with a system that (by radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be avoided, the device shall apply the brake as much as possible and minimise the risk of damage.
